John Edward: Essential Language Skills for Global Citizens
Private schools in Scotland hold the record for academic excellence and this has continued in 2018 with another row of excellent test results, further reinforced by individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other fields.
With over 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Private Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the highest level of service to students and their parents.
Private schools aim to prepare their students for further education at the highest levels, for the careers chosen by them and their country as global citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement an adapted educational curriculum, we are demonstrating how the modern language web continues to be a widespread and popular choice across schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, "If you speak to someone in a language they understand, your words come to them.
If you speak to him in your own language, your words will go to his heart.”
These words are a powerful reminder that we can't rely solely on English when we want to build relationships with people from foreign countries.
From the results of last year's exams, we can find that languages are leading the results lists, with the highest rate of passing grades among private schools.
A total of 68% of students who have studied foreign languages have received a maximum score of A.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72% of students had received the maximum grade A in Mandarin, while 72% of those studying German, 69% of those studying French and 63% of those studying Spanish also received the maximum grade A in Mandarin.
This shows that private schools in Scotland are supporting foreign languages as one of the vital skills that will undoubtedly be needed by children and young people in the future.
Currently, the branch of foreign languages is considered as important as the STEM branches (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of private schools and beyond.
A 2014 study by the United Kingdom's Employment and Skills Commission found that among the main difficulties employers faced in filling vacancies, 17 percent of them were related to a lack of language skills.
As a result, language skills are becoming more and more necessary for preparing young people for their future careers.
With the addition of jobs that require the mastery of foreign languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career a person chooses, if he has learned a second language, he will have real advantages in the future, as a possessor of such a long-term ability.
The ability to communicate directly with foreign people will automatically position a multilingual person above competitors.
According to a YouGov survey, which included over 4,000 adults from the UK in 2013, 75 percent of them were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by 15 people.
This is the reason why investing in language learning is important for today's children.
Mastering many languages, and especially mastering the languages of developing countries, will give children a better chance of employment.
Within Scotland, each school will be different in terms of the languages learned in them.
Some schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will offer languages that are considered to be the most important for the UK in the 2020 perspective, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interests, there will always be a variety of languages you can choose from in private schools, with pedagogical staff composed of field specialists.
Scottish private schools are committed to providing a school environment that will prepare children and "arm" them with the skills they need to succeed, regardless of the future.
At this time there is no denying the fact that in a global business environment, languages continue to be of vital importance for the future of the country, so this should be reflected in education.
Modern languages should really be considered as the “capacity of international communication”.
Private schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to Scotland's youth.
You have to do it right.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Private Schools.
