Harvard students are taking lessons on how to get enough rest.
A new course at Harvard University this year has involved all students to sleep more, in an effort to combat the growing culture of study 'masks' through the use of caffeine from these 'sleepers.'
One academic noted that world's number one university students often have no idea when it comes to the most basic things about how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, prepared the lecture course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start this course after he gave a paper on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
"At the end of it, a girl approached me and said, 'Why is this being told to me now, in my last year?'
She said no one had talked to her before about the importance of sleep - which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, included in the program for the first time this year, explains to students the essential elements of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, and also how it improves their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and the university's general director of medical services, said the university decided to introduce the course after finding that students were seriously deprived of sleep over the course of a week.
An hour-long course involves a range of interdisciplinary tasks.
On one side is a view of a convivial room, where students click on cups of coffee, curtains, athletes and books in order to explain to them the effects of caffeine and lighting and how athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep, as well as the importance of the sleeping routine.
In another part, participants were explained how long-term sleep deprivation increases the risks of heart attack, ischemia, depression, and cancer.
A map of the camp, with interacting icons, further encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know that the behavior of the students will not change immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know - just as you have a right to know - the health impact when you choose to smoke," added Prof. Czeisler.
The culture of pride to spend “a night of pay” continues to exist, he said, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students meant that sleep deprivation was an ever-increasing problem.
Ensuring you’ve got enough sleep, of a good quality, should be students’ ‘secret weapon’ to fight stress, fatigue, and anxiety, he said — even to avoid weight gain, because sleep deprivation leads the brain into a starving mode, making them starve.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies physical and chemical biology, helped Professor Czeisler prepare the course after attending one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to turn it into a course for the whole camp.
He hopes that the next step, is to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar study program before joining competing institutions.
Prof Czeisler recommended that students should set an hour clock when they should go to bed, and also when they should wake up, and be aware of the damaging effects of ‘blue light’ coming out of electronic screens and LED lighting, which can bring the rhythm of the smog into the biological environment.
