The creator of the World Wide Web plans to launch a new internet to compete with Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, the founder of the World Wide Web, is setting up a company that aims to rival Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of the technology legend, ‘Inrupt,’ is a company built by Berners-Lee’s open source platform, called ‘Solid’.
‘Solid’ allows users to choose where their data is stored and which persons are allowed access to a certain information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the goal behind Inrupt is "world domination."
"We have to do it now," he said of this innovative company.
"It's a historic moment."
The application uses Solid's technology to allow people to create "storage of their personal data on the network" or a POD.
It may contain contact lists, to-do lists, music lists, and other personal and professional tools.
It's the same as having available in a browser and at the same time Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify.
What is unique about the storage of personal data on the network, is the fact that it remains completely in the user's hands what kind of information they will access.
The company calls this "personal empowerment through data."
The idea for Inrupt, according to the company's CEO, John Bruce, is to bring together the right resources, processes and skills to help Solid be available to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform bought by IBM, several contracted developers to work on this project, and a community of volunteer coders.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world can create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team are not talking to Facebook and Google about whether or not they should introduce a total change where all of their business models are completely overturned at night.
"We're not asking for their permission."
In a post in Medium published on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that Inrupt's mission "is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem that helps protect the integrity and quality of the new network built on Solid."
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
Over the past few months, Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the debate over network impartiality.
While founding Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the consortium of the World Wide Web, the Network Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
"I'm very optimistic about this new era of networking," Berners-Lee added.
