The study by scientists at the National Trust for Scotland will follow the usual night-time nudists and those called soprano pipistrelles as well as the long-haired coffee and Daubenton nudists in the Inverewe Gardens, in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment will be placed at key points throughout the area to track the activities of the nudes at night throughout the season.
The NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct field studies using hand detectors.
The sound analysis that will be carried out by experts for all the recordings will determine the frequency of the sounds of the night nudes and what each species does.
Then, a report and a map of their habitat will be drawn up to give a detailed overview of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, a nature conservation adviser for NTS, hopes the findings will show which habitats are most important for night owls and how they are used by each species.
This information would help to determine the assets of the settlement management, such as the creation of pastures and how to maintain forests for night squirrels and other related species.
The number of night nudists in Scotland and across the UK has fallen sharply over the past century.
They are under threat from construction and development works that have an impact on the habitat and the loss of habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose hazards, such as stickers or chemical components of building materials, as well as pet attacks.
Naked people in the night are not blind.
However, due to their hunting habits at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching and waiting.
They use a sophisticated location-finding technique through sounds to accurately determine insects and obstacles during flight.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens, and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes night nudes very seriously.
There are ten trained experts, who regularly carry out studies, speech inspections and are sometimes involved in rescue programs.
The organisation has even set up the first and only reserve in Scotland dedicated to night owls in Threeave, Dumfries and Galloway, which serves as home to eight of the ten species of night owls in Scotland.
