"We have old buildings, lots of old trees and all the right habitat.
But there's still a lot of stuff about the nudes of the night that remains unknown, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us understand more about what they need to 'develop'."
He emphasizes the importance of carrying out checks on nudity at night before carrying out property maintenance work because there is a possibility that the unintentional destruction of a nest can kill up to 400 female and young nudity at night, thus exterminating the entire population of the area.
Night owls are protected and killing, harassing and disturbing them or destroying their nests is illegal.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish employee at the Night Nude Conservation Trust, encourages people to become part of the aid.
She said: "We still have a lot to learn about our night-time nudists and many of our species, we just don't know how their population is moving."
